# n8n Workflow Patterns

Battle-tested patterns for common workflow architectures.

## Pattern: Webhook Processor

Receive external events, validate, process, respond.

```
Webhook -> IF (validate) -> Process -> Respond
                         \-> Error Response
```

**Key rules:**
- Always validate webhook payload before processing
- Respond quickly (< 3s) - offload heavy work to sub-workflows
- Use "Respond to Webhook" node for custom response codes/bodies
- Store raw webhook payload for debugging

## Pattern: API Poller

Check an API on a schedule, process new items only.

```
Schedule -> HTTP Request -> Code (filter seen) -> Process -> Update state
```

**Key rules:**
- Track last-seen ID or timestamp to avoid reprocessing
- Use `Static Data` to persist state between executions
- Handle pagination (loop until empty page)
- Rate-limit API calls to avoid throttling

## Pattern: Batch Processor

Process large datasets in chunks to avoid timeouts and memory issues.

```
Trigger -> Fetch all items -> Split In Batches -> Process batch -> Merge results
```

**Key rules:**
- Split In Batches node with batch size 10-50 (API-dependent)
- Add Wait node between batches for rate-limited APIs
- Track progress for resumability
- Use Error Trigger workflow for failed batches

## Pattern: Error Handler

Catch and handle errors gracefully across the workflow.

```
Main workflow:  Trigger -> Process -> Output
Error workflow: Error Trigger -> Log -> Notify -> (optional) Retry
```

**Key rules:**
- Create a separate "Error Workflow" and link it in workflow settings
- Log error details: node name, error message, input data
- Notify via appropriate channel (email, Slack, webhook)
- Don't retry infinitely - set max retries in node settings

## Pattern: Data Sync

Keep two systems in sync (bidirectional or one-way).

```
Schedule -> Fetch source -> Fetch destination -> Code (diff) -> Create/Update/Delete
```

**Key rules:**
- Always diff before writing (don't blindly overwrite)
- Handle deletes carefully (soft delete preferred)
- Log every change for audit trail
- Use IF node to route creates vs updates vs deletes separately

## Pattern: AI Agent Workflow

LLM-powered processing with tool use.

```
Trigger -> AI Agent -> Tool nodes -> Process response -> Output
```

**Key rules:**
- System message sets behavior and constraints
- Connect tool nodes (Calculator, HTTP, Code) to the agent
- Set temperature 0 for deterministic tasks, 0.7+ for creative
- Add output validation after the agent (don't trust raw LLM output)
- Set reasonable token limits to control costs

## Pattern: Approval Flow

Human-in-the-loop processing with approval gates.

```
Trigger -> Prepare -> Wait for approval -> IF approved -> Process -> Notify
                                        \-> Reject -> Notify
```

**Key rules:**
- Use "Wait" node with webhook resume for async approval
- Include all context in the approval request (reviewer shouldn't need to look things up)
- Set timeout on Wait node (don't wait forever)
- Log approval/rejection with reviewer identity and timestamp

## General Rules

| Rule | Why |
|------|-----|
| One workflow, one responsibility | Easier to debug, test, reuse |
| Use sub-workflows for shared logic | DRY, single point of change |
| Name nodes descriptively | "Fetch User Orders" not "HTTP Request 3" |
| Set retry on failure for external calls | Networks are unreliable |
| Test with production-like data | Edge cases hide in real data |
| Pin test data on trigger nodes | Reproducible development and testing |

## Anti-Examples

| Bad | Why | Better |
|-----|-----|--------|
| One giant workflow with 50+ nodes | Impossible to debug or test | Break into sub-workflows |
| No error handling | Silent failures, data loss | Error Trigger workflow + notifications |
| Hardcoded credentials in Code nodes | Security risk, breaks on rotation | Use n8n Credentials |
| Processing all items without batching | Timeout on large datasets | Split In Batches |
| No logging/audit trail | Can't debug issues after the fact | Log key events and decisions |
